  "name": "sardine parsley pasta",
  "instructions": "spaghetti tossed with sardines, parsley, lemon juice, and pine nut breadcrumbs. Season with fennel powder — a pinch is canonical for the sicilian sardine profile.",
  "notes": "lemon juice, not zest.\n\nFENNEL POWDER IS CANONICAL HERE: pasta con le sarde traditionally uses wild fennel; fennel powder is the practical stand-in that carries the same anise-forward register. A pinch (or more) is the sicilian-sardine signature. Whole fennel seeds also work and give more textural bite.\n\nSUNFLOWER SEEDS ARE WELCOME — WHOLE ONLY, NEVER CRUSHED: toasted sunflower seeds scattered on top add a subtle nutty crunch alongside the pine nut breadcrumbs. Non-negotiable precondition: DO NOT CRUSH THEM. Whole toasted seeds only. Pine nuts tolerate being crushed to dust with breadcrumbs (that's exactly what pine nut breadcrumbs are); sunflower seeds do NOT. Crushed sunflower seeds turn the dish CHALKY — a gritty dry-mineral mouthfeel. Whole seeds work fine and add real texture; ground seeds ruin the dish. Same underlying property as the sunflower-seeds-in-red-pesto clash (see master-italian-tomato-sauce-and-pesto).
